This article is about an executive order issued by President Joseph R. Biden Jr. The order aims to prevent and combat discrimination based on gender identity or sexual orientation. It states that every person should be treated with respect and dignity, and should be able to live without fear. The order emphasizes that children should be able to learn without worrying about discrimination, and adults should be able to pursue their careers without facing mistreatment due to their personal lives or appearance. The order further states that healthcare and housing should be accessible without being subjected to sex discrimination. It highlights that all individuals should receive equal treatment under the law, regardless of their gender identity or sexual orientation. The order instructs the heads of each agency to review existing orders, regulations, and policies that relate to sex discrimination, and to consider revising or rescinding them as necessary to implement the statutes that prohibit sex discrimination. The order also emphasizes the need to address overlapping forms of discrimination, such as racial or disability discrimination. Each agency is required to develop a plan within 100 days to carry out the actions identified. The order includes definitions and general provisions, and states that it should be implemented consistent with applicable law and subject to the availability of appropriations.